  "prompt": "What is the meaning of \"i\" in iPhone?",
  "response": "The \"i\" in **iPhone** (and other Apple products like **iMac**, **iPod**, and **iPad**) originally stood for **\"internet\"** when Steve Jobs introduced the iMac in 1998. It was intended to signify the device's focus on internet connectivity, which was a major selling point at the time.  \n\nHowever, Apple later expanded the meaning of the \"i\" to represent other concepts as well, such as **\"individual,\" \"innovate,\" \"instruct,\"** and **\"inform.\"** Over time, the \"i\" became more of a branding element rather than a specific acronym, symbolizing Apple\u2019s design philosophy and user-centric approach.  \n\nIn the case of **iPhone**, the \"i\" has become synonymous with Apple's iconic smartphone, with no strict definition tied to it beyond its association with the brand.",
